			    STPJS 257</div>
  <p class="cont">in the greatest amount of good and glory to those who become the recipients of his law and
  ordinances.<span class="footRef">1</span> Blessing offered, but rejected, are no longer blessings,<span class="footRef">2</span> but become like the talent hid
  in the earth by the wicked and slothful servant;<span class="footRef">3</span> the proffered good returns to the giver; the blessing
  is bestowed on those who will receive<span class="footRef">4</span> and occupy; for unto him that hath shall be given,<span class="footRef">5</span> and he
  shall have abundantly,<span class="footRef">6</span> but unto him that hath not or will not receive,<span class="footRef">7</span> shall be taken away that
  which he hath, or might have had.</p>
  <p class="poem">Be wise today; &rsquo;tis madness to defer;<br>
      Next day the fatal precedent may plead.<br>
      Thus on till wisdom is pushed out of time,<br>
      Into eternity.</p>
  <div class="topic">Men are Judged According to Their Deeds</div>
  <p class="std">Our heavenly Father is more liberal in His views, and boundless in His mercies<span class="footRef">8</span> and blessings,<span class="footRef">9</span>
  than we are ready to believe or receive; and, at the same time, is more terrible<span class="footRef">10</span> to the workers of
  iniquity,<span class="footRef">11</span> more awful in the executions of His punishments,<span class="footRef">12</span> and more ready to detect every false
  way,<span class="footRef">13</span> than we are apt to suppose Him to be. He will be inquired of by His children.<span class="footRef">14</span> He says, &ldquo;Ask
  and ye shall receive, seek and ye shall find;&rdquo;<span class="footRef">15</span> but, if you will take that which is not your own,<span class="footRef">16</span> or
  which I have not given you,<span class="footRef">17</span> you shall be rewarded according to your deeds;<span class="footRef">18</span> but no good thing
  will I withhold from them who walk uprightly<span class="footRef">19</span> before me, and do my will in all things<span class="footRef">20</span>&mdash;who will
  listen to my voice and to the voice of my servant<span class="footRef">21</span> whom I have sent; for I delight in those who seek
  diligently to know my precepts,<span class="footRef">22</span> and abide by the law of my kingdom;<span class="footRef">23</span> for all things shall be made
  known unto them<span class="footRef">24</span> in mine own due time,<span class="footRef">25</span> and in the end they shall have joy.<span class="footRef">26</span> (Aug. 27, 1842.)
  DHC 5:134–136.</p>
  <div class="topic">FEMALE RELIEF SOCIETY&rsquo;S MEETING&mdash;REMARKS OF THE PROPHET</div>
  <div class="topic">The Church to Prevail Against All Evil Powers</div>
  <p class="std">President Joseph Smith arose and said, I am happy and thankful for the privilege of being
  present on this occasion. Great exertions have been made on the part of our enemies to carry me to
  Missouri and destroy my life;<span class="footRef">27</span> but the Lord has hedged up their way,<span class="footRef">28</span> and they have not, as yet,
  accomplished</p>
